1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Nf6 3. c4 e6 $5 {A sacrifice for development; this is an
Icelandic gambit. You can find the correct lines for Black in the opening
repertoire for Black.} 4. dxe6 Bxe6 5. Nf3 {Developing the knight to its best
position.} Nc6 6. Be2 {Developing the bishop and preparing 0-0.} Bc5 7. O-O Qd7
{Here White has a few interesting possibilities.} 8. Nc3 {Developing the
knight to its best position.} (8. d3 {following with Nbd2 and Nb3 is an
interesting option. White wants to push back Black's c5-bishop and get control
over the d4-square.}) (8. b4 $1 {A bold decision. White gives back his extra
pawn in order to fight for the initiative. This deflects one of Black's pieces
from the d4-square, allowing White to expand in the center.} Bxb4 9. d4 {
Threatening d5, and all Black's pieces became vulnerable suddenly.}) 8... O-O-O
9. a3 {Preparing b4, which is the main plan here due to the opposite wing
castling.} Nd4 10. Nxd4 Bxd4 11. Nb5 $1 {Threatening Nxd4 - winning the bishop
pair.} a6 12. Nxd4 Qxd4 13. d3 Bf5 14. Qb3 {Preventing Bxd3 due to Rd1 - and,
at the same time, threatening Be3!} Rhe8 15. Bf3 {Threatening on b7 and
removing the threat on e2.} (15. Be3 {Isn't very good after...} Rxe3 16. fxe3
Qxe3+ 17. Kh1 (17. Rf2 Ne4 $1 {And the 'd' pawn is pinned.}) 17... Qxe2 18.
Rxf5 Ng4 19. d4 Ne3 20. Rg5 g6 $44) 15... c6 16. Be3 $1 {Now Black gets his
pawn back. But White has the bishop pair and Black's castled position is in
danger.} Qxd3 17. Qb6 $1 {Taking advantage of this weak square.} Qd6 18. Rad1
Qc7 19. Rxd8+ Rxd8 20. Qb4 $14 {White earns a slight positional advantage and,
most importantly, a very easy to play position. Black has nothing he can do.
The rest of the game is instructive but does not concern our main subject.} Re8
