1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 {The problem with this move is that White can now
develop a piece and, at the same time, win a tempo.} 3. Nc3 Qd6 {Tiviakov's
speciality.} 4. d4 {Winning the centre.} Nf6 5. Nf3 {Developing with maximum
activity.} a6 6. g3 $1 {This move is very useful in this position for two main
reasons: 1. helps White to fight for the h1-a8 diagonal;. 2. prepares Bf4 at
the right time.} b5 7. Bg2 Bb7 8. O-O e6 9. Bf4 $1 {Now it's time to use the
g3 pawn.} Qb6 10. a4 $1 {This move is very strong because it threatens a5 and
also wants to open the position to take advantage of Black's lack of
development.} Bd6 11. Be3 $1 {Excellent move! White doesn't want to exchange
pieces and, moreover, the bishop is creating an 'x-ray attack', preparing d5
at the right time.} b4 12. a5 $1 Qa7 13. d5 $1 {Now it's time!} Bc5 14. dxe6 $1
{Sacrificing a piece for the initiative.} Bxe3 15. exf7+ Kxf7 16. Ne5+ $1 Ke7
17. Bxb7 Qxb7 18. Qd3 $1 {It's amazing how Sutovsky understands this position.
He wants to take on e3 with the queen, creating a lot of threats.} bxc3 (18...
Ba7 19. Rfe1 $1) 19. Qxe3 {Now it's all over for Black! The king has no escape.
This game clearly shows the right spirit for attacking the Scandinavian.} Nbd7
