1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 {The main line.} 4. d4 {Simply getting some
space in the centre.} Nf6 5. Nf3 {Developing with maximum activity.} c6 6. Ne5
{The knight is very strong here and the bishops are very flexible in this
position.} Be6 7. Nc4 Bxc4 8. Bxc4 {Now White has the bishop pair and a little
bit of space advantage.} e6 9. Qe2 {Leaving the bishop on c1 for a while; Bd2
is also possible but allows Qb6.} Nbd7 10. Bd2 Bb4 11. O-O {There is no need
in this position to take the risk of queen side castling - White has a solid
positional advantage.} O-O 12. a3 $1 Bxc3 13. Bxc3 {Two bishops are, in most
situations, superior to two knights.} Qc7 14. g3 {This move is always useful,
controlling f4 and giving the king some air.} b5 15. Bd3 Nb6 16. b3 a5 17. Qe5
$1 {Obviously! Without queens, the strength of the bishops increases.} Nbd5 18.
Bd2 Qxe5 19. dxe5 Nd7 20. Rfe1 Nc5 21. Bf1 $1 {Of course!} a4 22. b4 Na6 23.
